“The day after I graduated high school I moved to Arizona due to a job. My first night there I had my first drink. A guy from my co not led me into the bathroom and that was the night I lost my virginity. I didn’t k ow he took a video and shared it with the whole company. It was a few weeks after (and me still not knowing about the video) for a get-together to cone along. I drank too much and my friends (so I thought) led me home. One was also my housing supervisor, so he had access to a closed garage we didn’t. They sat me down on the couch and 10 minutes later they dragged me out to a tent and raped me.  The company sent me home when I tried to report it, and they got to keep their jobs. When I came home, my parents asked me if I had been flirting and what I was wearing (jeans and a loose sweater). They still said I asked for it. Combined with all the death threats from people at the company, I couldn’t take it. I packed up my life into a backpack and left for good. It still hurts sometimes. They act like it never happened when we talk.” -Anonymous VU⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
.⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
.⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
Thank you for sending in ‘YourStory’ to @VaginasUnitedVU. I hope you continue to be able to do what’s right for you. You are not alone. Sadly. I don’t know why pretending it didn’t happen is an option. You have a sister in me and the people who read your story that you touch. Thank you for being brave. There’s many of us out here just like you. I hope I get to meet you and hug you some day. It’s an honor sharing your story. -VU❤️💜⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
